nsists of three longer essays by Cavarero, Butler, and Honig, followed by shorter responses by a range of scholars that widen the dialogue, drawing on post-Marxism, Italian feminism, queer theory, and lesbian and gay politics. Together, the authors contest the boundaries of their common project for a pluralistic, heterogeneous, but urgent feminist ethics of nonviolence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aGender & Sexuality. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 4aPolitical Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aAdriana Cavarero.  aBonnie Honig.  aFeminism.  aJudith Butler.  aethics.  agender.  amaternity.  anonviolence.  asex.  athe body.1 aBattersby, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernini, Lorenzo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Judith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aButler, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavarero, Adriana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevenney, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForti, Simona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuaraldo, Olivia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHonig, Bonnie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHonig, Bonnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuzar, Timothy J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuzar, Timothy J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWoodford, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWoodford, Clare, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle 